Lower inflation and dovish comments helped pushed bond yields lower last week. The 10-year US Treasury yield was down by 27bps to 4.20%, while that of equivalent German bunds declined by 28bps to 2.36%.

Waller also stated that the Fed "could start lowering the policy rate just because inflation is lower". Given lower inflation data, this suggested it was more likely that the Fed would start easing policy in 2024.

US Q3 GDP growth was revised up by 0.3% point to 5.2% q/q annualised, driven by upward revisions to business investment  government spending. The October PCE core price index, a measure of core inflation that is key for the Fed, fell to 3.5% y/y, the lowest level since April 21.
